1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Okay. One and action.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Today is Saturday March 9, 2013. My name is Assam Kwame Jeffries of the Ohio State University and the Southern Oil History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

4
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:47,000
I'm with videographer Petna Delico in Albany, Georgia on the campus of Albany State University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

5
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:54,000
We are here with Mr. Sam Mahon. Thank you so much for being here with us.

6
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:01,000
I want to begin simply by asking you when and where were you born?

7
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:06,000
It was born in America's Georgia which is South Dakota County, Southwest Georgia.

8
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:12,000
And what year? Was it the date of birth? 1945.

9
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:18,000
1945. So the war is over.

10
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Some people say that World War II usher in this sort of new era of transformation and democracy. What was America's light when you were growing up?

11
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:42,000
I imagine it was like most small southern rural cities in that the lines of separation were very, very vivid, very stark.

12
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:55,000
As a child growing up, you tended to try to enjoy your childhood but there were instances where you just knew that things just were not right.

13
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:08,000
And a lot of that came about when you would look at your parents and see how they reacted to situations when white people were present.

14
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:20,000
You notice little subtle things like you look at your father and your mother and you notice how there's virtually no eye contact when they are talking and speaking with white people.

15
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Your father is always looking in a downward manner. Is it that eye contact with somehow create a confrontation?

16
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:43,000
You notice other things like how your community for instance, the old saying about across the railroad tracks was very true.

17
00:02:43,000 --> 00:03:01,000
No sidewalks, the roads were dirt at that time, no pavement anywhere. I grew up with an outdoor toilet. We had an outdoor toilet. We didn't get plumbing until I was a senior in high school.

18
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:18,000
My mother was a domestic worker. She worked in white people's home. That's what she did as employment. My father was a factory worker who worked in a basket factory that produced baskets for the contained fruit, large shipments of fruit.

19
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
But what were their names?

20
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:28,000
My father's name was Bergen Mahon. My mother's name was Lula Bell. My maiden name was Walker.

21
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:37,000
I was a seventh of six children. I was a sixth. I had a sister that younger than myself.

22
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:52,000
Other things that you pick up on like for instance, when you're totally dependent on white stuff for their services, for instance, there was always the...

23
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:02,000
There was what we call the policy man, the insurance agent who would come to do it or do other industries to collect the money for the policies.

24
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:09,000
They would simply come up to your house and not even knock and just simply walk into your house. That's how white agents.

25
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:16,000
That's how much they took liberty. That's how much they went control.

26
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:28,000
So of your everyday existence you saw these things. But it didn't really manage best in terms of you as a child, you know you accepted these things.

27
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:36,000
And of course, anytime you left the house your parents would always tell you, you knew your place, you knew what you could do and what you couldn't do.

28
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:43,000
And it was out of fear for your life that they did these things. So you grew up under those circumstances.

29
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:57,000
But I have to say that even though you internalize these things, it was something that you didn't really resist. You went along with it.

30
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:10,000
It was only until I became engaged in what was called. There was a group of ministers who would start a voter registration project called the Americas Voters League.

31
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:17,000
This was prior to any civil rights organizations coming to America. And I was probably in the 10th grade or something like that.

32
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:27,000
And began to work in terms of trying to talk to other students about voter registration and those kinds of things.

33
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:31,000
To you about 16? Yeah, about 1916-1961.

34
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:37,000
Exactly. And these are students in your high school? Yeah, exactly. And what did you go to school?

35
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:57,000
I graduated some of the county high school in America's Georgia. I went through the entire school system there and went from schools that had the old part bellied wood stoves and until finally getting their condition schools when I finally graduated from school.

36
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:06,000
So you become involved with this voter league? Yeah. And what led you to become involved with them?

37
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:16,000
I think it was more out of having something to do, I think. In fact, that's what led me to become more of an activist later on.

38
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:26,000
It was in a small town. You had very little outlets in terms of trying to do things that were outside of the norm.

39
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:35,000
And so anything that had a sense of being something different or then I was attracted to that.

40
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:43,000
How did your classmates respond to you when you start talking to them about some of the things that you're doing with the voter league?

41
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Well, some of them responded quite positively. And then those that did took it as a challenge.

42
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:07,000
And there was a very short time between that time and when stick activists came into the records. And so that further galvanized those people who had been receptive in the first place.

43
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:17,000
And so it was at that time that we sort of moved from that right into that activism within the movement, which later became America's movement.

44
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:24,000
Did your parents, what did they think about your early involvement, even before Snick gets there?

45
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:35,000
My parents were mainly disengaged. And I think a lot of it had to do. My father was a working man. He had very little conversation and he just worked.

46
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:46,000
My mom, as a domestic, was more receptive to conversation. She had no particular feelings about it.

47
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:55,000
But there was very little conversation in terms of what I was doing in terms of that kind of work and what happened.

48
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:17,000
But they were not against it. They were very supportive. And what I did, they were of course always fearful. But especially my father, who, but my mother was, she had fears also, but she was more likely to pull along with the things that I was doing at that time.

49
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
How about your siblings?

50
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:28,000
By that time, all the siblings were away from home. During this time, it was myself and my younger sister, who was three years younger.

51
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:40,000
And of course, she was not involved because she got pregnant before she finished school and moved away to Florida and started a family.

52
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:52,000
And so I was virtually left there, all my older brothers had joined the military, we're in service. And so there was very little interaction between me and my other siblings at that time.

53
00:08:52,000 --> 00:09:04,000
In fact, many of them know that I was involved in this until years later. I mean, they just didn't pay attention to what the things that was happening at my time.

54
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:14,000
So in this interim period between you start and you get your feet wet, you're beginning to become sort of publicly active.

55
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:20,000
And so are there other things that you're doing as well with the voters lead before you encounter a snake folk?

56
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:30,000
No, not at all. Just really going to school and trying to manipulate through that, some things that kids normally do in that period.

57
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:46,000
I worked outside jobs, I picked cotton. Before school opened up, I pulled up peanuts, I picked peaches, you know, you name it in field work.

58
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:53,000
And then also as a student in school, I got a job working at a clothing store, cleaning up and what have you.

59
00:09:53,000 --> 00:10:00,000
So I did the normal things that kids do at that time. If you can get a job, you know, then that's where I did.

60
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:08,000
What was some of, or when did you become engaged with snake?

61
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:23,000
Stick came into America's in late 1962. Don Harris, John Churchill, Ralph Allen, I believe, the first work to came in.

62
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:31,000
They were dispatched there from here, from Albany, by a private director, Charles Sherrod.

63
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:37,000
And at the time they were expanding their work in several counties around throughout the southern border area.

64
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:49,000
America was chosen because of the demographics and the dynamics there. And most of these rural counties blacks comprised full of 50% of the population.

65
00:10:49,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Medium income was like about maybe $1200 a year for blacks, you know, and it was maybe tripled that for white school, four or five times after white school.

66
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Schools of course were a second class. I never got a new book at all throughout the 12 years of school.

67
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:18,000
We always had books passed on to us. We knew that, you know how you got a book in school in the next class and you'd have all these names written into the books, you know.

68
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:25,000
So we knew as students that we were two or three years behind in terms of the books that we received.

69
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:35,000
But we had not your teachers at that time who cared for us. And we did the best they could with what they had.

70
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:45,000
And so we we cherish that. To the state we cherish that because they laid the ground was first to do the work that I feel that I began doing later on.

71
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:54,000
You're still in high school at the time. What do you think about these freedom writers that so many people call them?

72
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:02,000
As I said, anything that was new to a kid, one of the smaller town was exciting, interesting.

73
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:13,000
They came into America's. They had Northern dialects, you know, they were from college campuses. They bought books with them. Books that I had never seen before.

74
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:31,000
They set up what was called a SNCC house where they moved into these houses and immediately began to reach out to students and the pastors and ministers really could to begin to try and build workers to work on voter registration.

75
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:45,000
So the SNCC house became a hangout house for kids, you know, we would go there and we began doing things like printing leaflets and flyers on the old mammograph machines and handcrack machines.

76
00:12:46,000 --> 00:13:14,000
And the fact that they introduced us to black authors, you know, Richard Wright, James Baldwin, you know, the boy and all these people that we hadn't heard of gave us a whole sense of meaning, you know, and being, you know, and as a kid, it really, it really sparked an interest in us and made us want to come back to that house every day after school.

77
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:21,000
You know, see what they had to do, they wanted us to do for them, you know, so that's literally how it started, you know.

78
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:23,000
And what, what, what was the freedom house?

79
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:32,000
It would be a rental house, an old wood frame house, shotgun house that some might have read to them, you know, for little nothing.

80
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:41,000
It may have made out of head running water, you know, but it was just a meeting house and they slept there sometimes on the floor, sleeping bags, what happened, you know.

81
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:47,000
And so I even wound up spending the night there, you know, just hanging out at the SNCC house.

82
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:53,000
And that's how my activism began.

83
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:10,000
And the more I stayed there, the more my interest increased. And the more I recognized the duality of this system that we lived in, and that there was a chance it was up in the batter.

84
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:16,000
How did you get involved with the protest that the movie did?

85
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:26,000
We spent several months working on voter registration. We would canvas door to door through advocacy, and not only in the city, but we went out to the counties also.

86
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:28,000
And this is an anniversary.

87
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:30,000
Is it an anniversary for this? 63?

88
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,000
Yes, okay.

89
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:54,000
We recognized, and through Stiff made us recognize that the only way to form the power, the change in the dynamics of the system, was through getting people registered, choosing our own candidates, looking them to office, who would look after our own interests before change.

90
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:05,000
So it was going to be a time to recognize that voting was power. And so we spent our days, and even as a record on voter registration, we would go to the house to house.

91
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:07,000
We would take down names.

92
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:11,000
We would schedule times, and we could come back and pick them up to take them down the register.

93
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:23,000
We set up Freedom School, because we were talking about people who some who could not read or write, some who had mostly had never voted.

94
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:37,000
And so the Freedom Houses were places where we would organize, and teach people how to read and write, or at least pass the exams, the literacy test at that time.

95
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:47,000
It was a place of organizing, strategy, and what have you, what neighborhoods we would canvas, who would drive the cars to take them down.

96
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:58,000
It was also a place where we would taught each other, self defense techniques, not fighting back because we had accepted the principle of non-ballas.

97
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:10,000
But basically teaching us how to protect ourselves, and we were attacked, if we were attacked, how to curl up in a fetal position if you were beaten and kicked and what have you.

98
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:24,000
We would go through these scenarios of how if someone spat in your face, you know, how would you respond, and just prepare us for what we knew eventually was going to come.

99
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:26,000
And that they came?

100
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:38,000
That they came, we eventually moved from voter registration to begin and to test the laws of public accommodation.

101
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:42,000
And strange enough, this didn't come from stick workers, it came from the students themselves.

102
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:44,000
The young people, the young people.

103
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:45,000
You and your friends?

104
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,000
Yes.

105
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:54,000
Who said, we wanted to go to these places, you know, that had bought us, you know, discriminated against us.

106
00:16:54,000 --> 00:17:06,000
The main theory was the most visible place downtown. It was a place, and it was both, when I say visible, the interests were so stark, the differences.

107
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:14,000
The black interest was, you had to walk around the side of the theater down a dark alley, about 150 feet.

108
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:21,000
You woke up three fights of stairs and sitting about going to look at the theater.

109
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:28,000
So one night, 11 of us decided we were going to go to the front, entrusted to try to purchase tickets.

110
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:32,000
We stood there for about a half an hour and they wouldn't sell us tickets.

111
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:35,000
So we just stood there and then the police came finally.

112
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:42,000
And they asked us to disperse, we did not disperse the air, sitting with charge with this only conduct and figure to be an officer.

113
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:46,000
And it took us on a fatty wagon, took us off the jail.

114
00:17:47,000 --> 00:18:00,000
The next morning we went to Kuwait and they released us on probation, which was a 90 day probation.

115
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:07,000
And being kids, we didn't realize that if you got arrested again, you couldn't be bailed out.

116
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:13,000
And nobody took the time to explain to us that because one week later, I was arrested again.

117
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:19,000
And all of us from the original group, from the original 11 were arrested again.

118
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,000
And as a part of another demonstration.

119
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:24,000
And at the same theater.

120
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:37,000
And immediately they singled us out the four of us who had previously arrested and they sent us to prison, to sit at prison.

121
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:44,000
So you get arrested, you spend the night in jail, they pull you out immediately.

122
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:46,000
They put us in jail.

123
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:48,000
The next one we go back to court.

124
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:49,000
Same judge.

125
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:50,000
Same judge.

126
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:55,000
And they tell us that we have to immediately begin those sentences.

127
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:03,000
So at some point you realize, wait a minute, I'm about to do some time.

128
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:04,000
Yeah, exactly.

129
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:05,000
What are you thinking?

130
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:11,000
Well, we still been grasped that we wouldn't have to do this time.

131
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:19,000
We just felt as kids that somehow we were going to get out of this because there were two girls, two boys and two girls.

132
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:23,000
And so it happened overnight.

133
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:25,000
This is literally what they put us on the streets.

134
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:33,000
Well, the first day they took us, they put us in prison and took us out to do road work.

135
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:37,000
Cutting grasses and cutting grass and things like that.

136
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:49,000
Well, the local ministers went to City Hall and demanded, which was really something at its time, that they not put the women on the street, the girls on the streets.

137
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:54,000
So they did not.

138
00:19:54,000 --> 00:20:04,000
My friend and I, the other guy, we decided to, we just sat down and sat and were not going to work.

139
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:12,000
So when we did that, they took the two of us down to the county jail, for the city of the county jail.

140
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:32,000
We put us in a hole, which was about a four by a six foot concrete enclosure, with a little sit at the bottom about 46 inches wide, where they would each day put in a piece of bread and a cup of water.

141
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:37,000
Well, we decided we weren't going to eat them on a hunger strike.

142
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:42,000
So we're total darkness for about seven days.

143
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:48,000
We did, we fasted for about seven days until we passed out.

144
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:53,000
Now, when you, in close proximity, was the other hole, were you together or were you accepting?

145
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:56,000
We got in the same hole.

146
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:06,000
And so they took us out of the hole and we were just literally passed out.

147
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:17,000
They took us to the hospital and filled us with some fluids and then we went back to the jail and we went back to work.

148
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:20,000
We went to work two days after that.

149
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:29,000
And the jobs that we did, ran some cutting grass on the side of the streets, picking up garbage on weekends.

150
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:36,000
The worst job was cleaning out the city switch.

151
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:38,000
They saved that specially for us.

152
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:43,000
None of the other prisoners had to do this, who were in all kinds of crimes, right?

153
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:47,000
You think these switch treatment plants, where they had these long pools?

154
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:51,000
Well, America's had three of them. I believe it was three.

155
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:57,000
And they would take us there with an armed guard.

156
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:03,000
And there was a dump truck that found us and it gave us two shovels.

157
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:11,000
And it cost all day to shovel out these pools of raw sewage, of sewage at the treatment plants.

158
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:17,000
I believe we did that maybe once a week, twice a week.

159
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:22,000
Maybe twice a week, yeah, twice a week, I believe something like that.

160
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:28,000
But that was very specifically for us because we were those no good-adgettakers.

161
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:32,000
And this is three months. I mean, you got 90 days, you're young.

162
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:39,000
You do. Your parents, they must be, you obviously worried.

163
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:42,000
What did they say?

164
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:48,000
Of course, my father was most visibly upset.

165
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:53,000
My mother was also upset. My father was just angry, I think.

166
00:22:53,000 --> 00:23:00,000
As I said before, he never really, he was just fearful of my life.

167
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:08,000
And the fact that I had kind of disobeyed him and that you got in and got yourself in the trouble really now.

168
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:16,000
But they stood by me, they supported me, especially my mom.

169
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:18,000
She would bring things to her.

170
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:25,000
And then working on the street was different than other people who were just jailed.

171
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:28,000
I mean, no people, we're just incarcerated all the time.

172
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:35,000
So working on the street gave us an opportunity to have people pass us by to come by and they would see us working on the street.

173
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:39,000
And they would let us know what's going on in the movement.

174
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:45,000
They would give us money sometimes by things like that.

175
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:49,000
I started smoking cigarettes, cigarettes, cigarettes, things like that at that time.

176
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:52,000
Unfortunately, yeah, I was smoking.

177
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:56,000
But it was in kind of doing an outlet for us to get information.

178
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:59,000
It's the kind of freedom we get on the outside.

179
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:01,000
We would work all day long.

180
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:05,000
And in the day, they'd bring us back to the jail, say, don't lock us up at night.

181
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:12,000
And at night, we would watch other people who were arrested on the day being brought in.

182
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:22,000
And to see other people continuing to fight and to continue to demonstrate gave us really that's what got us through.

183
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:27,000
How did the jailer's treacher?

184
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:36,000
Well, the jailers were very racist, very, very cold, very...

185
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:42,000
Just no sympathy at all for what we were doing.

186
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:50,000
The sheriff of something kind with that time was the sheriff's chapel, where the whole was, where the best way they kept us in the whole.

