00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:36,000
She ran for office of Justice of the Peace.

423
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:38,000
And what years is this?

424
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:43,000
This was 1965.

425
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:52,000
On the dearly election, as people were voting, she and three other women,

426
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:58,000
Mamie Campbell, who was the wife of the America's movement president, Rebun Campbell,

427
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:04,000
Gloria Wise, who is now deceased and Lena Turner, who lives in Atlantic City now,

428
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:11,000
they decided to try to vote in the white voting line.

429
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:15,000
When they refused to leave, they were all arrested, put in jail.

430
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:26,000
And that led to a daily deluge of demonstrations, protests, demand in their release.

431
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:31,000
These demonstrations went on every day.

432
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:37,000
And during that time there were several confrontations with the police,

433
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:43,000
several people were beating, throwing in jail.

434
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:46,000
One day the white merchants of the city decided to get together,

435
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:52,000
and this was about maybe three or four days after they had been arrested.

436
00:43:52,000 --> 00:43:56,000
The merchants got together and decided they were going to bond the marriage jail.

437
00:43:56,000 --> 00:43:57,000
The white merchants?

438
00:43:57,000 --> 00:44:02,000
The white merchants, because they feared more trouble, more, as they call it,

439
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:06,000
more confrontation in the streets.

440
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:13,000
So faced with that, the women decided that we're not going to accept it.

441
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:20,000
They wrote a letter which we have and now we now have that letter and I request that we've been keeping.

442
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:24,000
And it says simply that these are the same merchants they've stood by.

443
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:35,000
It's black kids, boys and girls were beaten and assaulted for simply trying to demonstrate

444
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:37,000
their rights.

445
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:43,000
And now you've come forward to debond us out of jail and they cite hypocrisy of them,

446
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:51,000
not speaking out then, but one debond us out, simply to keep quiet and what have you.

447
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:55,000
So they refused to bond, they stayed in jail.

448
00:44:55,000 --> 00:45:01,000
And about a week later they were released, fellow Judge released them,

449
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:05,000
unconditionally, dropped the charges and what have you.

450
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:12,000
And declared that segregated colonizers were no longer retaliated in South Dakota,

451
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:14,000
so that was significant.

452
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:21,000
A significant victory that really propelled more people who saw power in their numbers.

453
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:29,000
And so each victory was one that really unified us and swelled the numbers in terms of people

454
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:32,000
willing to get out there and protest.

455
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:45,000
And you were with the America's movement for up and two and through 1966.

456
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:48,000
Yeah, 1966, that's correct.

457
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:52,000
And then you head down to Mississippi to two balloons.

458
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:54,000
Head to Mississippi.

459
00:45:54,000 --> 00:46:00,000
What happened was that SNCC had started a program of providing scholarship money for kids

460
00:46:00,000 --> 00:46:08,000
who weren't you go to school, provided that you come back to your community and do some work,

461
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:10,000
continue doing some work.

462
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:16,000
And so I jumped at the opportunity, I didn't know anything about two glue.

463
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:20,000
I just knew other stick people who were up in Mississippi, you know.

464
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:25,000
Went to Mississippi, went to two glue, had planned the major in social sociology.

465
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:38,000
Got the campus and recognized that two glue was had been at the forefront of a lot of civil rights activity in Mississippi.

466
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:48,000
And at that time, the to my knowledge had the only was the only black institution protest against the war of the Vietnam.

467
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:56,000
And so I joined that movement and became very involved in activities there in Mississippi.

468
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:08,000
Later on went to places like Greenville, working with a sharp opposite what have you, things like that.

469
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:14,000
I left there after two years because most of my time I've been spent actually as an activist off campus.

470
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:19,000
It was difficult to really settle in as a student after having gone through what happened in America

471
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:24,000
and seeing the conditions that in a lot of places simply were not changing.

472
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:27,000
And there was more work to be done.

473
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:33,000
So once you become an activist, you don't settle down anymore, you continue it.

474
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:39,000
And to this day, you know, you want to be in the fight, you know, somehow.

475
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:40,000
There was no going back.

476
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:42,000
No going back, never going back.

477
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:47,000
And so after you leave two glue, what do you do after that?

478
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:59,000
I, while it took a little, I met, there was a lawyer who was from America's who had been run out of America

479
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:06,000
and a white lawyer who was forced to flee America's because he had been sympathetic to the movement.

480
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:08,000
His name was Warren Forson.

481
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:15,000
His brother at the time happened to be Ben Forson, who was Secretary of State in Atlanta.

482
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:23,000
Well, Forson had, was head of the America School Board at that time, I believe,

483
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:29,000
and had fought to integrate the library here in America's.

484
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:34,000
The thing that really pushed him over the age and where the white community was the fact that he,

485
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:40,000
there were two students who had been arrested, born a girl.

486
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:45,000
One was the first student, one of the first students to integrate the white high school,

487
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:49,000
Robert Tina Freeman, and her boyfriend.

488
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:53,000
They were at Parking one night, as kids, you know.

489
00:48:53,000 --> 00:48:59,000
And so the policeman pulled up alongside them and decided to charge them with,

490
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:04,000
and these were an explosion, fornication, what had he, and arrested them.

491
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:11,000
Now, we feel that this was brought on by the fact that she had integrated in America's high,

492
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:14,000
and she was doing it gradually.

493
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:20,000
And we feel that they put these charges on them to keep her from being the first black to graduate from America's high.

494
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:28,000
Well, Forson was, he took that case on, and he defended them in court, successfully.

495
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:32,000
But he was never able to live in the city after that.

496
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:37,000
He was founded by the Ku Klux Klan. His own neighbors turned against him.

497
00:49:37,000 --> 00:49:41,000
People he had gone to church with turned against him.

498
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:45,000
He was afraid to sit by his window at night because of threats.

499
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:48,000
So he has finally moved to Atlanta.

500
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:58,000
And so, fast forward to 67, 68.

501
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:08,000
I'm at a lecture at Tugulu, and Forson happens to be there.

502
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:15,000
And I see him, and we speak to each other, and we connect.

503
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:19,000
And so I tell him that I'm going to be leaving to Luprace and going back to America.

504
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:23,000
So he said, what are you going to do? I said, well, I don't know.

505
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:28,000
So he said, why don't you go back to Atlanta and see my brother?

506
00:50:28,000 --> 00:50:33,000
I'll call my brother and tell him that you're looking for some work.

507
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:41,000
So I get back to Atlanta, and I go to the Secretary of State's office.

508
00:50:41,000 --> 00:50:49,000
And he sends me to the Georgia Department of Archives, which is on the Secretary of State's office.

509
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:56,000
And I go in there, and I take a job as an apprentice in paper conservation, restoration.

510
00:50:56,000 --> 00:51:03,000
And I learned the craft, and I wound up standing there for about 15 years.

511
00:51:03,000 --> 00:51:06,000
Well, 12 or 15 years, actually.

512
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:15,000
But before I left there, I began to study photography and began to take photographs,

513
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:18,000
and I opened up an art gallery while I was still working here.

514
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:19,000
Moving in that gallery?

515
00:51:19,000 --> 00:51:22,000
Ancestral Art Gallery.

516
00:51:22,000 --> 00:51:33,000
And when I felt comfortable enough, I resigned the job and I left and did the gallery full time.

517
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:40,000
And I think being in the movement prepared me for that, because I'd always been intrigued by images.

518
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:51,000
And of course being in the movement, a lot of times it was only images that propelled people, signs that were made, photographs that were taken.

519
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:57,000
And so I began to do that as a street photographer.

520
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:03,000
And I grew up in the movement of images by other artists as well.

521
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:16,000
But that was a way of continuing that to this and because it allowed me to elevate the work of African American artists who didn't have venues for the most part in places like Atlanta.

522
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:25,000
Whose work was had been diminished by traditional, you know, outbursts, galleries and what have you.

523
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:36,000
And marginalized, you know, so that led me to another form of activism in terms of trying to project the arts more positively than the African American community.

524
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:38,000
And it was a place where people could come.

525
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:43,000
It was not just a gallery to buy art, but it was a place where people could come to be informed.

526
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:48,000
We had poetry sessions there.

527
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:51,000
We had public meetings there.

528
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:56,000
They had to do with things in terms of in the community.

529
00:52:56,000 --> 00:53:02,000
So it was an outlet to continue that activism, but in a different, you know, a different way.

530
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:09,000
I want to wrap up in a second by talking about the American movement, remember it.

531
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:12,000
I want to go back just quickly, just briefly if we can.

532
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:19,000
And ask you about you were working, you were engaged in anti-war protests.

533
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:23,000
But then you were drafted.

534
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:36,000
I was drafted. Yes. In fact, that's, I was never, I was drafted in 69.

535
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:47,000
And when I went into the military, I had basic training at Fort Benning, Georgia, which was hours drive from a hometown.

536
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:55,000
Where most people go on to advance training when you finish basic, they kept me there at Fort Benning.

537
00:53:55,000 --> 00:53:57,000
They never gave me a security clearance.

538
00:53:57,000 --> 00:54:05,000
And they said it was because of my arrest record in America.

539
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:10,000
So instead of sending me on to an advanced training, they sent me into what was called a hold of a company.

540
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:17,000
And with that meant, with that means is that it's a company where all you do is duty work.

541
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:27,000
You dig ditches, you cut grass, you clean the trees, bathrooms, and what have you for the offices and what have you.

542
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:37,000
It was a place where, during this time, it was common for people who had been gotten arrested during the Vietnam War.

543
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:41,000
They gave you choice of either going to prison or going to the war.

544
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:46,000
So here I was in this group.

545
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:53,000
And they literally woke you up every morning at 6.30 and you had a duties to do.

546
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:56,000
It would be digging ditches, they cut grass.

547
00:54:56,000 --> 00:55:04,000
In fact, one of the duties was to build an archery course for the offices, which literally go into this jungle like wood, wooded area.

548
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:09,000
And dig highways through and cut highways through to dig up and set up these targets.

549
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:12,000
And it was another form of punishment, you know.

550
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:15,000
I did that for a whole year.

551
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:21,000
And at the end of the year, someone decided they were going to close a training camp at Fort Benning.

552
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:24,000
So they closed on a training camp, the center.

553
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:31,000
And so if everybody either got shipped to Vietnam or Germany, I got sent to Germany.

554
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:35,000
I still didn't have a security clearance.

555
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:42,000
They gave me an MOS, they gave me a duty, which was clerk type, is just the name.

556
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:50,000
And so they sent me to Europe to what was called a material command, about a five hour drive from Paris, France.

557
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:58,000
They literally put me in an office behind a big office, but in the back.

558
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:00,000
But then there's going to cheer.

559
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:04,000
And I sent there all day long.

560
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:10,000
I did nothing.

561
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:14,000
So what I did in my time was that I picked up a camera.

562
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:19,000
That was when I first picked up the camera.

563
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:25,000
I used my weekends. I bought a car from a guy who was coming back to the States, paid him 100 bucks for a car.

564
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:34,000
And I would take off on weekends, drive to the countryside, drive to Paris, a six hour drive, five hour drive.

565
00:56:34,000 --> 00:56:39,000
And I spent all my time doing that.

566
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:42,000
But for the rest of that, my service time.

567
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:48,000
And 71 I was released in New Jersey.

568
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:55,000
And then I came back and went back to work at the State Archives.

569
00:56:55,000 --> 00:57:01,000
And so you sort of migrated back to a certain extent to America's.

570
00:57:01,000 --> 00:57:11,000
Because now you're spearheading this effort to keep the America's movement alive on the minds and in the memories of people.

571
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:14,000
That is correct.

572
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:24,000
And 2007, my stuff and several other veterans of the Americas movement decided to convene on America's once again to.

573
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:37,000
Because one of the things we recognize as movement veterans is that a lot of us hadn't passed on these stories to our kids.

574
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:43,000
And we don't have no idea what some of the parents had been through.

575
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:51,000
A lot of the history had been lost, a lot of these significant things that we talked about in terms of the Americas for.

576
00:57:51,000 --> 00:57:56,000
And the women who were arrested for trying to vote.

577
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:07,000
All of this was going to be lost if we didn't take up the mantle and try to collect this information and put it out there.

578
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:11,000
So we met in America's in 2007.

579
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:17,000
We met at a place which was around zero.

580
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:20,000
A place called Bottoms funeral home.

581
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:27,000
It was one of the places where we would feel a director who and his whole family had allowed us to use this place for a meeting place.

582
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:31,000
He was the sole bells bondsman for the Americas movement.

583
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:35,000
People got arrested. He was the only bondsman who could bail for us.

584
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:45,000
We went back there and met his daughter who was also incarcerated at Leesburg, who's now the director of the funeral home there.

585
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:48,000
She allowed us to come there and be back once again.

586
00:58:48,000 --> 00:58:53,000
And we decided that every two years we would want to have a tribute.

587
00:58:53,000 --> 00:59:05,000
But in a long range ago it was to somehow either bill or constitute a museum there, but the housing materials that we had begun to collect.

588
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:12,000
And we were all about the business of collecting photographs, some of us had kept things from that time.

589
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:21,000
Flyers, we had formed a newsletter among the simmers at that time.

590
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:25,000
And we published a newsletter out of the Smith House with an old memory graph machine.

591
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:28,000
It was called the Voice of the Americas in Southwest Georgia.

592
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:38,000
It was a six page mirror graph that, and we assigned people as reporters, you know, we have people going to other counties here reporting on what happened in this county.

593
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:44,000
We have copies of those that we kept in our archives.

594
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:52,000
And so that was a long range mission.

595
00:59:52,000 --> 01:00:03,000
The other niches we had to do with trying to provide scholarships for kids who were doing things today in that community service things in that community.

596
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:14,000
We have started a mentoring program of kids trying to get adults to mentor kids who we see falling through the cracks, you know.

597
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:18,000
That mission has led us a lot of different paths.

598
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:27,000
We are connecting with the grandkids of some of the veterans of the movement who had no idea that that parents were involved.

599
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:39,000
Fascinating thing is that each celebration we bring out the photographs and we went through all the newspapers that covered the Marcus Moome.

600
01:00:39,000 --> 01:00:43,000
Marcus Times recorded literally did no reporting because it didn't work to get out.

601
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:50,000
But papers like Atlanta Journal, Columbus Ledger, Macintosh Telegraph, Atlanta Daily World.

602
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:58,000
We come through their archives and we reproduce photographs, I mean, the news articles, photographs.

603
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:06,000
And we, it's a very kind of a crew display because we just blew it up with what we had.

604
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:12,000
Zeroct machine, at some point we want to get these things digitized and then they can have better presentation.

605
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:18,000
But we have these four by six frame pieces that we display every celebration.

606
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:26,000
And on one occasion we had a young lady walk through the, and she was looking at the photographs.

607
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:30,000
She saw a picture of a woman who was pregnant.

608
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:34,000
And she said, that's my mother.

609
01:01:34,000 --> 01:01:38,000
Okay, and that's me and her belly.

610
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:45,000
So her mother had not told her what she had done.

611
01:01:45,000 --> 01:01:55,000
And she just literally went well at that time because she had no idea that her mother was one of those foot soldiers at that time.

612
01:01:55,000 --> 01:02:02,000
So it's those things like that that propels you even more to know that the work you're doing is important.

613
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:08,000
We are committed to, to, to, to, to send this project to, to fruition.

614
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:14,000
We're trying to make some connections with the local university there who want to help us with our oral history project.

615
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:21,000
And hopefully other things will come as a result, as also as well.

616
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:27,000
This happens to be Jimmy Connors of Alma Mater as well in America, sir.

617
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:35,000
So it's not just about, it is about, very much about remembering the movement, but it's also about keeping the spirit of the movement.

618
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:36,000
Exactly.

619
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:37,000
A lot.

620
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:38,000
Exactly.

621
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:54,000
It's, we want to, in fact, the whole idea of the scholarship is to nurture a whole new generation of young activists to get them to see that they stand on the shoulders of some people who just made some tremendous miscyclophages.

622
01:02:54,000 --> 01:03:04,000
And we want them to know that, that, that this work has to go on and it won't only go on if they take initiative and, and take the lead.

623
01:03:04,000 --> 01:03:07,000
And, because of the times we pass to them.

624
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:13,000
And so we, we expect them to do it, you know.

625
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:16,000
It's expected of them to do that.

626
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:21,000
And so that's, that's been our mission. Every, every two years we, we do that.

627
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:24,000
Sam Mahon, thank you very much.

628
01:03:24,000 --> 01:03:25,000
Thank you.

629
01:03:25,000 --> 01:03:26,000
Appreciate it.

630
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:27,000
Thank you.

631
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:28,000
Thank you.

632
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:29,000
Thank you.

633
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:30,000
Thank you.

634
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:31,000
Thank you.

635
01:03:31,000 --> 01:03:39,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

